tspan.tspan: Comparing hospital processes is a critical but notoriously difficult aspect of public policy and healthcare
improvement. Existing methods often fail to account for the complex, intertwined nature of patient journeys
and the many events that occur simultaneously. This makes it challenging to identify concrete areas for
We propose a novel method that models patient pathways as probabilistic processes. By integrating concepts
from Markov chains and geometry, we developed a quantifiable measure to determine the "distance" between
two different hospital processes. Distance in this context means a way of numerically quantifying the structural
disimilarity between processes, with a distance of zero meaning two processes are identical.
Our new method provides a robust and efficient way to evaluate a wide range of hospital process models. This
allows for powerful subsequent analyses, such as clustering similar processes, identifying best practices, and
pinpointing specific bottlenecks for process redesign. By providing a tangible, numerical way to compare
processes, our tool empowers clinicians and policymakers with the actionable data they need to make informed
